[{"id":30298,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>ii</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;Sand Meyer reaction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iv</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;Gatterman reaction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;Wurtz reaction</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi>iii</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;Fittig reaction</p><p>The Wurtz reaction is a very useful reaction in the fields of organic chemistry and organometallic chemistry for the formation of alkanes.</p><p>In this reaction, two different alkyl halides are coupled to yield a longer alkane chain with the help of sodium and dry ether solution.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30334,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"113\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1fbfb1d7-33ad-4c47-b056-4d63998ee0be-image.png\" width=\"147\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"68\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7f21f6aa-8c50-4d70-ba8f-9ae86259d9d3-image.png\" width=\"207\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"72\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/987413bc-efc3-4d73-bd5a-1e55e9a43483-image.png\" width=\"162\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"74\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/de7723f9-adc7-4a78-bf14-50d2ca9c044c-image.png\" width=\"167\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img height=\"278\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4fe4b447-ccd9-46e2-a413-95cb4f11b820-image.png\" width=\"631\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30354,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>CHC<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>Br","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>CCH<sub>3</sub>C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>Br","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>Br","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>Br"],"answer":3,"solution":"In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> (nucleophilic bimolecular substitution) inversion takes place<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mtext>stearic&#160;hindrance</mtext></mfrac></math><br /><br />Rate of R&ndash;X is 1&deg; &gt; 2&deg; &gt; 3&deg;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30389,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Mg}-\\mathrm{Br}$ bond","$C$ - $Mg$ bond","$C$ - $B r$ bond","$\\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{H}$ bond"],"answer":1,"solution":"Bond between C of organic molecule and metal atom","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":30308,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Changing the base from&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mmultiscripts><mi>OR</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#8854;</mo></mmultiscripts></math> will have no effect on reaction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>","Changing the concentration of base will have no effect on reaction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math>","&nbsp;Doubling the concentration of base will double the rate of both the reactions","&nbsp;Changing the concentration of base will have no effect on reaction <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>First reaction is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>SN</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math> in which rate does not depend on conc. of nucleophile.</p><p>Second reaction is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>2</mn></math> reaction in which rate depends on conc. of base.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30262,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/18a01690-2474-48d1-90d0-fcf9edbdf64e-9896791_A.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 97px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/67ae6727-73da-4763-9aa2-86dead1bd743-9896791_B.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 127px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/54893881-c598-41e1-ad18-8788c65d9785-9896791_C.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 285px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3003156f-3e8a-4884-9a80-06104124c2a7-9896791_D.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 145px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":1,"solution":"In alcoholic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KOH</mi></math>,&nbsp;it does not undergoes&nbsp;elimination reaction due to the absence of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>, as it has extensive&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi></math>-branching.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30237,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["\\(\\text { (III) } > \\text { (I) } > \\text { (II) } > \\text { (IV) }\\)","\\(\\text { (IV) } > \\text { (I) } > \\text { (II) } > \\text { (III) }\\)","\\(\\text { (III) } > \\text { (IV) } > \\text { (II) } > \\text { (I) }\\)","\\(\\text { (II) } > \\text { (IV) } > \\text { (III) } > \\text { (I) }\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XKL271XGqfqdzHvTCfYDl-2sjn5gAAIRM0GdVFcTYrk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30274,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dafb5141-f34b-4449-8134-7be5c2856051-image.png\" style=\"width: 164px; height: 60px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b669d451-6df5-4dbf-8803-8ea61de4d934-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 60px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a4bccdf6-4370-442b-89ad-6330e30139cb-image.png\" style=\"width: 166px; height: 60px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5e7a4018-3cb9-40f6-bf22-7bc646ba4d10-image.png\" style=\"width: 236px; height: 60px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In the first step the given alkyl halide that is 2-bromo-3-methyl butane reacts with Mg in presence of dry ether to form a grignard reagent,This grignard reagent reacts with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;to form a hydrocarbon (B)which has a&nbsp; chiral carbon.</p><p>In the reaction with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;grignard reagent behaves as a strong base.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/707bd95b-2ecd-4fe9-a95b-629827e5a6c2-24-08-2022.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 175px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30318,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f37e4859-469b-4cc4-a71a-f12e2efe110e-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/360fbace-aa98-45b5-9d82-2a4f4b0e872f-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 95px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dd7a2b0b-b76d-4859-95cd-9d2271e8301e-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 79px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d9b94e2e-5fde-4751-9395-9ade76f0b4f1-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 114px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4807ac05-bb51-4fd7-a9bd-e93df505f9e8-fdd845d1-dec0-4c70-ba7c-4da85649a177-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 101px;\" /><br />In polar protic solvent <math><msub><mrow><mtext>S</mtext></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mtext>N</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>1</mtext></mrow></msup></mrow></msub></math> mechanism is favourable hence reaction complete via <math><msub><mrow><mtext>S</mtext></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mtext>N</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>1</mtext></mrow></msup></mrow></msub></math> mechanism.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30222,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{NO}_2, \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CN}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{ONO}, \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{NC}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{ONO}, \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CN}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{NO}_2, \\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{NC}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8TSer-l2sZiu75Engq6SEUVTsSrZf2OCUYcB5dXV2lI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30362,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Acetone","Propanol-1","Propene","Propanal"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/CC7fc8IWbvRXfEH-Ut2kHTF1WPnuLEXsd09KSevvuUQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30286,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>-Butyl ethyl ether","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> -Methyl pent-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>-ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></math> -Dimethyl butane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> -Methyl prop-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>-ene"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;is a very strong base and a weak nucleophile due to its&nbsp;bulkiness. So it will give&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp; elimination reaction as follows.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cc58184-cda6-4bee-8778-12e8f71c4eb9-3cc07b9a-944f-4118-a1d5-68f3fe903562-image.png\" style=\"width: 670px; height: 147px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30332,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/531c8f1a-89e8-4da7-bbea-eca000e1a8f5-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 83px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6b64123e-016a-4221-b56f-3d5f38772fe0-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 107px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/68bac18a-2d37-4399-bbb5-e9ef0538caf7-image.png\" style=\"width: 145px; height: 108px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cf131d28-7e50-4e96-96a2-b37fefc99571-image.png\" style=\"width: 145px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Here, the dehydrohalogenation goes by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>1</mn><mi>cb</mi></math>, and the most stable carbanion formation is favoured. Which will be formed&nbsp;in option&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;compound.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/597e843b-5f5b-477b-b53c-e5fd1e139ac1-89044442-1a75-495a-a8fb-d6caee87413e.jpg\" style=\"width: 543px; height: 231px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30224,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/F1e799PZr4Y4O6MiVN1S0ptdKC2Usn5YXYlhSfeQCdo.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ebdZIKNISpOEWQlp8p98MHVOjANeE1tyhbYFvvrDYI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{11.25 \\times 10^{-3}}{112.5}=\\frac{x \\times 10^{-1} \\times 10^{-3}}{93} \\\\ & x \\times 10^{-1}=93 \\times 0.1 \\\\ & x=93 \\mathrm{mg}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30270,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The given alkane&nbsp;2,2,5,5- tetramethylhexane&nbsp;has two types hydrogen, hence, it forms two different structural isomers on chlorination.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9884fd62-3f7e-43fd-adcc-1797ef236059-83942cca-4909-47ac-96d7-c852de2f9932-9894330.png\" style=\"width: 355px; height: 462px;\" /></p><p>Total numbers of isomers are equal to three as second molecule is optically active.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30380,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Wwf6naXR-O4tuI8xn-V0gXftJvtqjPQzHIM1mVa74mM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/FEISXlGNGoq-hRzQg03tMT1oNmht175LMpYm0FqWGqM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QH3NS0fHxnIPytAb8aOnroTmJOiemTRZIjKyvLiJ5Io.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m6mbq36J9sdcq_v2Malx0HvDJi9gcF4dIbfYdnrQ5vg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":30361,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{HBF}_4 / \\Delta$","$\\mathrm{HBF}_4 / \\mathrm{NaNO}_2, \\mathrm{Cu}, \\Delta$","$\\mathrm{CuF} / \\mathrm{HF}$","$\\mathrm{Cu} / \\mathrm{HF}$\n0"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cwJiC1cMaViV7FU8PZ4_NO0QEVST3ar7yeLxAyb-j8A.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30385,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["equimolar mixture of 1 and 2-butene","predominantly 2-butene","predominantly 1-butene","predominantly 2-butyne"],"answer":1,"solution":"Saytzeffs product","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":30353,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["CH<sub>3</sub>F &lt; CH<sub>3</sub>Br &lt; CH<sub>3</sub>Cl &lt; CH<sub>3</sub>I","CH<sub>3</sub>F&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>I&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>Br &lt;&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>Cl","CH<sub>​3</sub>F &lt; CH<sub>3</sub>Cl &lt; CH<sub>3</sub>Br &lt; CH<sub>3</sub>I","CH<sub>3</sub>Cl &lt;&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>Br&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>F&nbsp;&lt;&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>I"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>C-halogen bond length totally depends on the electronegativity difference between Carbon and halogen. The more the difference and&nbsp;the less is the bond length. The electronegativity order of halogens is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math>. Hence, the correct order of increasing C-halogen bond length is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p><p>Or we can say that as the size of halogen increases C-halogen bond length also increases.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null}]